result.execSummary:
The defendant Brandy Garrison was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • 2nd-Degree Recklessly Endangering Safety [Modifiers: Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.30(2).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
Court ordered defendant to pay all applicable court costs and surcharges.
Defendant shall provide a DNA sample for the Data Bank and pay all appropriate costs. 
As to all costs and surcharges, Court orders amounts payable during the period of probation. If revoked, DOC shall collect up to 25% of prison funds.  Remaining balance to be paid during the period of extended supervision. Any unpaid amount is ordered to convert to a civil judgment.

Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor. Court advised defendant that her voting rights are suspended and she may not vote in any election until her civil rights are restored.

No new offenses.
No contact with victims Kenya J. and Cornell D.

Anger management and follow through with treatment recommendations.
Any conditions deemed appropriate by agent.
AODA assessment and follow through with treatment recommendations.

Court orders defendant to serve 60 days upfront- REPORT DATE: 1/15/16.
Court imposes and stays 60 days to be used at the discretion of the agent.

ADA Adamson places negotiations on the record.  Defendant changes plea to GUILTY as to amended charge.  Defendant examined as to her plea, advised of her Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.  Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived her rights. Plea questionnaire received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  Defendant is advised she is a convicted felon and may not possess any firearms or body armor.  Defendant is advised she is unable to vote in any election until civil rights are restored.  Defendant further advised that if she is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for January 7, 2016 at 08:30 am.
